Severe storms wreaked havoc in Southern California, leaving 12,000 without power.
Tragedy struck when a hillside collapsed in Elysian Park, killing a man and injuring another.
The region faced multiple challenges, including rescues from collapsed homes and a 200-vehicle logjam on California Highway 18.
Mudslides, floods, and road closures plagued the area, with concerns of more disasters looming.
Despite the chaos, rescue efforts persisted, with authorities evacuating vulnerable communities.
The relentless rain and snow have claimed lives and caused widespread destruction, emphasizing the region's vulnerability to nature's wrath.
